column2: St. Pauli Landing Bridges & Old Elbe Tunnel
column3: t. Pauli Landungsbrücken (landing stages) is a 700-meter-long pontoon facility. Ten flexible bridges connect the pontoons with the mainland. Harbor tours, ferries and passenger ships leave from this water "station". Guests for the musical “The Lion King” can also depart from here to the theater at the opposite side of the Elbe.  Visitors can stroll around shops, cafes and restaurants while enjoying the view of the harbor. The former passenger terminal on the river promenade has been listed as an historic monument. At the western end is the entrance to the old Elbtunnel (Old Elbe Tunnel). The striking clock tower forms the eastern end of the building.
column5: Bei den St. Pauli-Landungsbrücken 8, 20359 Hamburg, Germany

column3: Huge fountain with up to 60 m high fountain in a lake in front of a city centre backdrop.

Speicherstadt (lit. 'warehouse city') is the world's largest complex of warehouses, spanning an area of 260,000 square metres. It was built into the Elbe river between 1883 and the late 1920s on thousands of oak poles as a free economic zone in Hamburg's port. Speicherstadt's beautiful neo-gothic brick architecture makes for an exciting contrast to the modern steel-and-glass constructions of neighbouring HafenCity.
